					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/a-random-day" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1841781); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1841781&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204538" alt="A Random Day" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1841781)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/a-random-day" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1841781); return false;" >A Random Day</a></span> <span class="odate time_1556217291 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">25 Apr 2019 18:34</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4229967">
									

<p>The Ambrose format was stale the moment the second restaurant list was posted, and has failed to get better since. Every time I see an Ambrose format, I know I'm just going to read a list of goofy-sounding dishes that reference better articles and are capped off by uninteresting reviews. Other GOI formats are thematically consistent with their group but manage to innovate within the confines of their format to tell interesting stories; Ambrose's format simply parrots itself over and over again. Something needs to change.</p>

							</div>

								
					
